{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659914"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:17:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:17:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21088"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13963"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80686"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of tissue is shown below. The image displays a cross-section of a tubular structure lined by a single layer of cells with centrally located nuclei. The cells appear approximately equal in height and width.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely represented in this histological section?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchiole of the lung","Kidney tubule","Large intestine","Blood vessel","Oesophagus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a cross-section of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ekidney tubule\u003C/strong\u003E. Kidney tubules are characteristically lined by simple cuboidal epithelium, which consists of a single layer of cells that are approximately as tall as they are wide (cube-shaped), with centrally located nuclei. This epithelial arrangement is specialized for absorption and secretion functions in the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiole of the lung\u003C/strong\u003E - Bronchioles are lined by simple columnar or cuboidal epithelium with ciliated cells and Clara cells, but would typically show a more irregular lumen and surrounding smooth muscle.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - The large intestine is lined by simple columnar epithelium with goblet cells, which would appear taller than wide and contain mucin-filled vacuoles.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessel\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood vessels are lined by simple squamous epithelium (endothelium), which appears as a thin layer of flattened cells with flattened nuclei.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E - The oesophagus is lined by stratified squamous epithelium, which would show multiple layers of cells becoming progressively flatter toward the lumen.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimple cuboidal epithelium is also found in other structures such as thyroid follicles, sweat glands, salivary gland ducts, and pancreatic ducts, but the tubular arrangement with a distinct lumen is most characteristic of kidney tubules in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Simple cuboidal epithelium consists of a single layer of cube-shaped cells with centrally located nuclei.","Simple cuboidal epithelium is found in kidney tubules, thyroid follicles, and small ducts of many glands.","Simple cuboidal epithelium functions in secretion and absorption in various organs."],"references":["Epithelial Tissues: Simple Cuboidal Epithelium. Flikr. Image accessed under CC0 1.0 license: https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/146824358@N03/41681552432/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80686"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21823"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21823"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VKjIjdS2GPYXdKDHFcVmpnrVq783tW.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/VKjIjdS2GPYXdKDHFcVmpnrVq783tW.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":846}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80686"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-12T12:22:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T10:25:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13963"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attribute